<DOC><DOCNO> AP890531-0095 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 1052EST</FILEID><FIRST>u i PM-BorderDeath 3rdLd-Writethru a0540 05-31 0318</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Border Death, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0540,0323</SECOND><HEAD>U.S. Citizen Killed in Fighting On Thai-Burmese Border</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: Insert 2 grafs after 4th, ``Fighting has ...'' to UPDATE withMotley's background. Pickup 5th pvs, ``U.S. Embassy ...'' Delete last pvs,``Soldier of ...'' to conform.</HEAD><DATELINE>MAE SOT, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A U.S. citizen working for the magazineSoldier of Fortune died today of gunshot and shrapnel wounds afterhe was caught in fighting on Burma's border with Thailand, policesources said.   Lance Eugene Motley, 32, was brought to Mae Sot hospital Tuesdaynight and died this morning, medical staff at the hospital said.His hometown was not known immediately.   Police said Motley apparently crossed into Burma three days agowith Karen rebels and went to their camp at Kaw Moo Ra, which hasbeen besieged by Burmese troops since May 18.   Fighting has been raging in jungle areas of this border regionsince Burmese troops launched an intensive offensive last Octoberagainst rebels fighting for autonomy from the central government.   Free-lance journalist Alan Dawson, who is based in Bangkok, saidhe met Motley after the American arrived in Thailand three weeksago. He said Motley told him he was a correspondent for Soldier ofFortune and had worked in the past in Central America.   Dawson said Motley planned to base himself in Bangkok to coverSoutheast Asia for the monthly magazine, which is based in Coloradoand specializes in combat and weaponry.   ``He had never been out of the American hemisphere and was veryeager to see what was happening in this part of the world,'' Dawsonsaid.   U.S. Embassy spokesman Neil Klopfenstein said only that anAmerican citizen died this morning ``after an incident on theThai-Burma border.'' He refused to release details.   The medical sources, who asked not to be named, said Motley wasbrought to the hospital with gunshot and shrapnel wounds to theface and body.</TEXT></DOC>